Jeopardy Analysis

Elizabeth Wickes

October 27, 2014

Data description

Collection and preparation

There were a total of 7961 players were imported, representing the subset of players who were detected to be from the United States and all duplicates removed. Duplicates were defined as entities with matching name and winnings values.

Data were pulled from player statistics HTML pages from J-Archive!. Example page:
http://j-archive.com/showplayerstats.php?player_id=8000.

Players were scraped in and associated data gathered. Occupational statements were aligned to the 2010 SOC code system. 28% of the players are failing to match with a controlled SOC code. Some additional SOC codes and groups were added to increase this matching. The curated version of the SOC code system is available here.

All code to produce the associated CSV files is located in an IPython Notebook available for viewing and download here. All original player and analysis files are available within this github repository.

The data have been split to only look at players participating in 2003 and after due a rules change that removed the maximum number of games each participant may compete in. The frequencies of players participating in numbers of games are charted below.

Exploring the impact of Ken Jennings

The majority of plots and other descriptives involving winnings will utilize a dataset that excludes Ken Jennings. Ken is the highest winning player ever on Jeopardy!, with a total of $3,162,085.00. The standard deviation for the set of players after 2003 with Ken is $60,874.44 and is $38,146.19 when Ken is removed. His winnings have a z-score of 51.574 when compared to the data set of including his value, and 82.3215 when excluding him. This z-score goes down to 29.8769 when looking just within the subset of players who have participated in more than one game.

Data Mean SD
2003 and after, all players $22,549.61 $60,874.44
2003 and after, excluding Ken $21,832.82 $38,146.19

The distribution of winnings is highly skewed to the right and lacks a normal distribution. However, the distribution of winnings for players participating in just one game (indicating that they played without winning) is less skewed, but still not normal. The data below include Ken Jennings.

Plots

Unless mentioned otherwise, all plots are using the data from after 2003.

Exploration of winnings and categorical data

The data below are all excluding Ken Jennings.

Several of the SOC major codes only have 1-5 players, so a subset of tabulations was created for better comparision between the groups.

Plots showing the impact of Ken Jennings

Winnings over year of the show

boxplot(noken$winnings ~ noken$year, data = noken)

Plots comparing all players who have only won one game versus more than one, including Ken Jennings. There are 5685 players who have only appeared on a single game (71.4106%) and 2276 have won at least one game (28.5894%).

Frequency of players within major SOC codes and game winners or not, using 2003 and after data.
